 Swami (1823-1874). Weiss narrates a history of Hindu modernization that demonstrates the transformative role of Hindu ideas, models, and institutions, making this text essential for scholarly audiences of South Asian history, religious studies, Hindu studies, and South Asian studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHinduismxHistoryy1765- 0aHistory (General). 0aHistory of Asia. 0aReligion (General). 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  acentrality of elite religion.  acosmopolitan reform movements.  ahindu modernization.  ahindu studies.  ahinduism.  ahistory of hindu modernization.  aimportant local figure.  ainfluence of western ideas and models.  amargin of colonialism.  aramalinga swami.  areligious change.  areligious studies.  asouth asian history.  asouth asian studies.  atamil shaiva poet and mystic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520973749zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520973749zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97